<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="OTA4">
<l>neṟivāca ṟāṉēyāy niṉṟāṉai yaintu</l>
<l>poṟivācal pōrkkatavañ cātti – yaṟivāṉā</l>
<l>mālamara nīḻa laṟanālvark kaṉṟuraitta</l>
<l>vālamamar kaṇṭat taraṉ</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>He who stood as the very portal to the path, by closing the portal of</l>
<l>the senses that are five, [which is] the battle door, [him] Hara  knows</l>
<l>in whose throat the poison rests, who that day taught</l>
<l>the Dharma to the Four in the shade of the banyan.<note>This first mention of Śiva (who recognises the superior power of Viṣṇu) mentions, besides the Sanskrit name Hara and the throat blue from the poison that rose from the milk ocean, also the form of Dakṣiṇamūrti, the deity seated under the banyan tree when teaching the four sages, the one form of Śiva with a formulaic attribute in the Caṅkam corpus several times, such as in Kalittokai 81.9: āl amar celvaṉ, “the lord residing by the banyan tree”.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
